## {#checkin-kernels data-menu-title="Check-in: comparing kernels"}

[Check-in]{.slide-title}

<hr>

::: {.teal-text .body-text-m}
1. What accuracy would you expect from the linear SVM on the circular data? Why can't it do better?

2. What is one advantage of the RBF kernel over the polynomial kernel when the data structure is unknown?

3. How should `gamma` and `C` be chosen in practice?
:::

. . .

1. Near 50–60% — no straight line can separate an inner cluster from an outer ring, so the linear SVM is forced to misclassify roughly half of one class.

. . .

2. The RBF kernel adapts to local structure without committing to a specific polynomial form. The polynomial kernel requires guessing an appropriate degree $d$; RBF can approximate a wide range of boundaries by tuning `gamma` alone.

. . .

3. Both `C` and `gamma` should be chosen using **cross-validation** on the training data (e.g., `GridSearchCV`). Never select them by evaluating on the test set.

